      "desc": "Facilities, outdoor.",
      "narrative": "The facility has sections of the perimeter fence that do not meet the requirements:\n-On the south side of the facility, the fencing used at the main gate measures approximately 83 inches (6 feet 11 inches).\nThere is a gap above the fence that measures approximately 14 inches.\n-On the east side of the facility, there is a section of perimeter fence adjacent to the cheetah van (Gate 7) where the fence\nmeasures approximately 90 inches (7 feet 6 inches).\n-On the south side of the facility behind the old elephant exhibit, there are two gates in the perimeter fence that remain\nopen during operating hours and are not maintained with an attendant.\nFailure to provide an appropriate perimeter fence may result in animal escape or allow persons or other animals to\ninteract with the regulated animals. All outdoor housing facilities must be enclosed by a perimeter fence that is of sufficient\nheight to keep animals and unauthorized person out. Fences less than 8 feet high (96 inches) for potentially dangerous\nanimals, such as but not limited to, large felines (e.g., lions, tigers, leopards, cougars, etc.), bears, wolves, rhinoceros,\nand elephants, or less than 6 feet high for other animals must be approved in writing by the Administrator. The fence must\nbe constructed so that it protects the animals in the facility by restricting animals and unauthorized persons from going\nthrough it or under it and having contact with the animals in the facility, and so that it can function as a secondary\ncontainment system for the animals in the facility. It must be of sufficient distance from the outside of the primary\nenclosure to prevent physical contact between animals inside the enclosure and animals or persons outside the perimeter\nfence. Such fences less than 3 feet in distance from the primary enclosure must be approved in writing by the\nAdministrator. Correct by ensuring that all species requiring a perimeter fence are completely enclosed within an\nadequate perimeter fence that meets all requirements. Alternatively, a variance may be requested in writing and sent to\nthe APHIS Administrator. Correct by 18-AUG-2026.\nThis inspection and exit interview were conducted with Facility Representatives.\nAdditional Inspectors:\nMark Sanderbeck, ANIMAL CARE INSPECTOR n"
    }
  ],
  "narrative": "3.127(d) \n   \nFacilities, outdoor. \nThe facility has sections of the perimeter fence that do not meet the requirements: \n \n-On the south side of the facility, the fencing used at the main gate measures approximately 83 inches (6 feet 11 inches). \nThere is a gap above the fence that measures approximately 14 inches.  \n-On the east side of the facility, there is a section of perimeter fence adjacent to the cheetah van (Gate 7) where the fence \nmeasures approximately 90 inches (7 feet 6 inches). \n-On the south side of the facility behind the old elephant exhibit, there are two gates in the perimeter fence that remain \nopen during operating hours and are not maintained with an attendant. \n \nFailure to provide an appropriate perimeter fence may result in animal escape or allow persons or other animals to \ninteract with the regulated animals. All outdoor housing facilities must be enclosed by a perimeter fence that is of sufficient \nheight to keep animals and unauthorized person out. Fences less than 8 feet high (96 inches) for potentially dangerous \nanimals, such as but not limited to, large felines (e.g., lions, tigers, leopards, cougars, etc.), bears, wolves, rhinoceros, \nand elephants, or less than 6 feet high for other animals must be approved in writing by the Administrator. The fence must \nbe constructed so that it protects the animals in the facility by restricting animals and unauthorized persons from going \nthrough it or under it and having contact with the animals in the facility, and so that it can function as a secondary \ncontainment system for the animals in the facility. It must be of sufficient distance from the outside of the primary \nenclosure to prevent physical contact between animals inside the enclosure and animals or persons outside the perimeter \nfence. Such fences less than 3 feet in distance from the primary enclosure must be approved in writing by the \nAdministrator. Correct by ensuring that all species requiring a perimeter fence are completely enclosed within an \nadequate perimeter fence that meets all requirements. Alternatively, a variance may be requested in writing and sent to \nthe APHIS Administrator. Correct by 18-AUG-2026. \n \nThis inspection and exit interview were conducted with Facility Representatives.\n\nAdditional Inspectors: \nMark Sanderbeck, ANIMAL CARE INSPECTOR n",
